WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:25.120
The

00:25.120 --> 00:28.600
Elephants Child by Rudyard Kipling

00:28.600 --> 00:35.600
Part 1. The Elephants Child wants some answers.

00:35.600 --> 00:46.600
In the beginning, elephants had noses. They had large noses, but they could not pick things up with them.

00:46.600 --> 00:57.600
One day the Elephants Child began to ask everybody questions. He always asked a lot of questions.

00:57.600 --> 01:01.600
He asked his aunt, the ostrich.

01:01.600 --> 01:04.600
Why have you got long feathers?

01:04.600 --> 01:12.600
The ostrich was angry with the Elephants Child. She punished him and sent him away.

01:12.600 --> 01:18.600
Don't ask questions, Elephants Child. She told him.

01:18.600 --> 01:23.600
The Elephants Child then went to his uncle, the giraffe.

01:23.600 --> 01:26.600
Why have you got spots?

01:26.600 --> 01:38.600
He asked the giraffe. His uncle, the giraffe, was angry with the Elephants Child. He punished him and sent him away.

01:38.600 --> 01:43.600
Don't ask questions, Elephants Child.

01:43.600 --> 01:46.600
He told him.

01:46.600 --> 01:52.600
The Elephants Child now went to his aunt, the hippopotamus.

01:52.600 --> 01:55.600
Why have you got red eyes?

01:55.600 --> 02:03.600
He asked his aunt. The hippopotamus was angry and she too punished the Elephants Child.

02:03.600 --> 02:06.600
Don't ask questions.

02:06.600 --> 02:08.600
She told him.

02:08.600 --> 02:14.600
The Elephants Child now went to his uncle, the baboon.

02:14.600 --> 02:17.600
Why do you like melons?

02:17.600 --> 02:18.600
He asked.

02:18.600 --> 02:21.600
Why are they good to eat?

02:21.600 --> 02:26.600
The baboon was angry and he punished the Elephants Child.

02:26.600 --> 02:32.600
Don't ask questions. Elephants Child.

02:32.600 --> 02:35.600
He told him.

02:35.600 --> 02:40.600
One day the Elephants Child had a new question.

02:40.600 --> 02:43.600
What does the crocodile eat?

02:43.600 --> 02:45.600
He asked everybody.

02:45.600 --> 02:49.600
Be quiet Elephants Child.

02:49.600 --> 02:52.600
Everybody shouted at him.

02:52.600 --> 02:57.600
His uncles and aunts were angry with the Elephants Child.

02:57.600 --> 03:01.600
They all punished him for a long time.

03:01.600 --> 03:04.600
He was very unhappy.

03:04.600 --> 03:09.600
He went away for a walk in the forest.

03:10.600 --> 03:13.600
Part 2.

03:13.600 --> 03:19.600
The Great, Gray, Green, Limpopo River.

03:19.600 --> 03:25.600
The Elephants Child met the Cola Cola bird in the forest.

03:25.600 --> 03:29.600
He told the Cola Cola bird everything.

03:29.600 --> 03:32.600
My father punished me.

03:32.600 --> 03:34.600
My uncles punished me.

03:34.600 --> 03:37.600
And my aunts punished me.

03:37.600 --> 03:39.600
He said.

03:39.600 --> 03:42.600
What does the crocodile eat?

03:42.600 --> 03:44.600
Do you know?

03:44.600 --> 03:48.600
The Cola Cola bird thought for a moment.

03:48.600 --> 03:50.600
Then he said.

03:50.600 --> 03:58.600
Do you know the Great, Gray, Green, Limpopo River?

03:58.600 --> 03:59.600
Yes.

03:59.600 --> 04:02.600
Replied the Elephants Child.

04:02.600 --> 04:04.600
I know it.

04:04.600 --> 04:06.600
Go there.

04:06.600 --> 04:10.600
The Cola Cola bird told the Elephants Child.

04:10.600 --> 04:13.600
You can ask there.

04:13.600 --> 04:16.600
I'll go there immediately.

04:16.600 --> 04:20.600
The Elephants Child decided.

04:20.600 --> 04:30.600
The Elephants Child walked through the forest until he came to the Great, Gray, Green, Limpopo River.

04:30.600 --> 04:34.600
Then he saw a python snake.

04:34.600 --> 04:36.600
Excuse me.

04:36.600 --> 04:37.600
He said.

04:37.600 --> 04:40.600
But is there a crocodile here?

04:40.600 --> 04:42.600
Yes.

04:42.600 --> 04:45.600
The python snake told him.

04:45.600 --> 04:48.600
A crocodile lives here.

04:48.600 --> 04:50.600
Good.

04:50.600 --> 04:52.600
Replied the Elephants Child.

04:52.600 --> 04:54.600
What does he eat?

04:54.600 --> 05:00.600
The python was angry now and he punished the Elephants Child.

05:00.600 --> 05:05.600
Don't ask questions Elephants Child.

05:05.600 --> 05:08.600
He told him.

05:08.600 --> 05:11.600
The Elephants Child walked some more.

05:11.600 --> 05:15.600
He walked on something big.

05:15.600 --> 05:18.600
It was the crocodile.

05:18.600 --> 05:21.600
The Elephants Child looked down.

05:21.600 --> 05:24.600
Where is the crocodile?

05:24.600 --> 05:27.600
He asked politely.

05:27.600 --> 05:32.600
The crocodile opened one eye very slowly.

05:32.600 --> 05:36.600
He looked at the Elephants Child.

05:36.600 --> 05:42.600
Come here Elephants Child.

05:42.600 --> 05:45.600
He said quietly.

05:45.600 --> 05:48.600
I'm the crocodile.

05:48.600 --> 05:49.600
Good.

05:49.600 --> 05:51.600
Cried the Elephants Child.

05:51.600 --> 05:54.600
What do you eat?

05:54.600 --> 05:57.600
Come here.

05:57.600 --> 06:00.600
The crocodile told him again.

06:00.600 --> 06:05.600
The Elephants Child came very close to the crocodile.

06:05.600 --> 06:11.600
The crocodile opened his mouth very wide.

06:11.600 --> 06:15.600
He held the Elephants Child by the nose.

06:15.600 --> 06:17.600
Today?

06:17.600 --> 06:19.600
Said the crocodile.

06:19.600 --> 06:28.600
I think I'll eat an Elephants Child.

06:28.600 --> 06:31.600
Part 3.

06:31.600 --> 06:36.600
The Elephants Child and the Crocodile.

06:36.600 --> 06:40.600
The python snake arrived at that moment.

06:40.600 --> 06:42.600
He said to the Elephants Child.

06:42.600 --> 06:45.600
The crocodile will eat you, my friend.

06:45.600 --> 06:48.600
You must pull as hard as you can.

06:48.600 --> 06:51.600
Pull, my young friend.

06:51.600 --> 06:52.600
Pull!

06:52.600 --> 06:57.600
The Elephants Child pulled and he pulled.

06:57.600 --> 06:59.600
It was no good.

06:59.600 --> 07:03.600
His nose was still in the crocodile's mouth.

07:03.600 --> 07:08.600
The crocodile also pulled as hard as he could.

07:08.600 --> 07:12.600
He pulled and he pulled.

07:12.600 --> 07:17.600
The Elephants Child's nose began to grow longer and longer.

07:17.600 --> 07:25.600
Suddenly, the Elephants Child gave an extra hard pull and he was free.

07:25.600 --> 07:28.600
He sat back on the ground.

07:28.600 --> 07:34.600
His nose was very long now and very warm.

07:34.600 --> 07:41.600
He put it into the great, grey, green lipopo river for a moment.

07:41.600 --> 07:44.600
Why are you doing that?

07:44.600 --> 07:47.600
Asked the python snake.

07:47.600 --> 07:49.600
My nose is too long.

07:49.600 --> 07:52.600
The Elephants Child told him.

07:52.600 --> 07:57.600
Perhaps the river will make it small again.

07:57.600 --> 08:01.600
Your nose will always be like that now.

08:01.600 --> 08:03.600
The python told him.

08:03.600 --> 08:05.600
But I don't like it.

08:05.600 --> 08:07.600
Cried the Elephants Child.

08:07.600 --> 08:10.600
Perhaps you like it one day.

08:10.600 --> 08:12.600
The python said.

08:13.600 --> 08:16.600
But it isn't a nose anymore.

08:16.600 --> 08:20.600
It's too long for a nose.

08:20.600 --> 08:23.600
We'll call it a trunk.

08:23.600 --> 08:28.600
The Elephants Child was not very happy at all.

08:28.600 --> 08:33.600
At that moment, a mosquito flew onto the Elephants Child's head.

08:33.600 --> 08:39.600
The Elephants Child lifted his trunk and hit the mosquito.

08:39.600 --> 08:42.600
The mosquito flew away.

08:42.600 --> 08:45.600
A trunk is a good thing.

08:45.600 --> 08:47.600
The python said.

08:47.600 --> 08:50.600
It's very useful.

08:50.600 --> 08:56.600
The Elephants Child began to play with his new trunk.

08:56.600 --> 08:58.600
He picked up some grass.

08:58.600 --> 09:01.600
He ate the grass happily.

09:01.600 --> 09:05.600
Now tell me something.

09:05.600 --> 09:07.600
Said the python.

09:07.600 --> 09:11.600
Do people hit and punish you?

09:11.600 --> 09:14.600
Do you like that?

09:14.600 --> 09:16.600
Of course not.

09:16.600 --> 09:18.600
Replied the Elephants Child.

09:18.600 --> 09:21.600
I don't like it at all.

09:21.600 --> 09:24.600
The python smiled at him.

09:24.600 --> 09:26.600
Now you've got a trunk.

09:26.600 --> 09:28.600
He said.

09:28.600 --> 09:32.600
Now you can hit and punish them.

09:32.600 --> 09:36.600
The Elephants Child smiled too.

09:36.600 --> 09:38.600
That's an idea.

09:38.600 --> 09:40.600
He said slowly.

09:40.600 --> 09:45.600
A very good idea.

09:45.600 --> 09:47.600
He walked home.

09:47.600 --> 09:53.600
When he arrived, all his uncles and aunts were happy to see him.

09:53.600 --> 09:56.600
Come here Elephants Child!

09:56.600 --> 09:58.600
They cried.

09:58.600 --> 10:02.600
The Elephants Child moved towards them.

10:02.600 --> 10:04.600
He smiled happily.

10:04.600 --> 10:12.600
One by one he punished his uncles and his aunts with his new trunk.

10:12.600 --> 10:15.600
Where did you get the new nose?

10:15.600 --> 10:18.600
They asked him.

10:18.600 --> 10:20.600
It's not a nose.

10:20.600 --> 10:23.600
The Elephants Child told them.

10:23.600 --> 10:25.600
It's a trunk.

10:25.600 --> 10:28.600
I asked the crocodile what he eats.

10:28.600 --> 10:31.600
Then he gave me the trunk.

10:31.600 --> 10:34.600
We want trunks too!

10:34.600 --> 10:37.600
All the Elephants cried.

10:37.600 --> 10:43.600
They ran off to the great, grey, green Limpopo River.

10:43.600 --> 10:47.600
When they found the crocodile, they asked him.

10:47.600 --> 10:51.600
What do you eat?

10:51.600 --> 10:55.600
The crocodile pulled their noses.

10:55.600 --> 11:01.600
And now all Elephants have got trunks.

11:04.600 --> 11:08.600
Pigs is Pigs by Ellis Parker Butler.

11:08.600 --> 11:13.600
Part 1. The correct price for pigs.

11:13.600 --> 11:18.600
Mr. Flannery worked for the Interurban Express Company.

11:18.600 --> 11:22.600
The company delivered parcels all over America.

11:22.600 --> 11:26.600
This morning Mr. Flannery was very angry.

11:26.600 --> 11:30.600
His customer Mr. Morehouse was also very angry.

11:30.600 --> 11:32.600
You decide.

11:32.600 --> 11:34.600
Shouted Mr. Flannery.

11:34.600 --> 11:37.600
He indicated the box in front of him.

11:37.600 --> 11:40.600
The box contained two small guinea pigs.

11:40.600 --> 11:43.600
They were happy to eat their food.

11:43.600 --> 11:46.600
You can pay for them and take them away.

11:46.600 --> 11:49.600
Or you can leave them here.

11:49.600 --> 11:54.600
But rules are rules, Mr. Morehouse.

11:54.600 --> 11:56.600
You're an idiot.

11:56.600 --> 11:59.600
Shouted Mr. Morehouse.

11:59.600 --> 12:03.600
The company rules are very clear. Look!

12:03.600 --> 12:07.600
Mr. Morehouse indicated a book on the counter.

12:07.600 --> 12:10.600
Then he read aloud.

12:10.600 --> 12:18.600
Domestic pets and boxes, Franklin to Westcoat, 25 cents each.

12:18.600 --> 12:21.600
These are domestic pets. They're in boxes.

12:21.600 --> 12:24.600
And they came from Franklin to Westcoat.

12:24.600 --> 12:27.600
I'll pay 25 cents each.

12:27.600 --> 12:32.600
There are two of them. I'll pay you 50 cents.

12:32.600 --> 12:35.600
Mr. Flannery picked up the rule book.

12:35.600 --> 12:38.600
Now he began to read what it said.

12:38.600 --> 12:41.600
I know they're domestic pets.

12:41.600 --> 12:43.600
Mr. Flannery said angrily.

12:43.600 --> 12:49.600
And the price for domestic pets is 25 cents.

12:49.600 --> 12:53.600
But they're also pigs. I know that too.

12:53.600 --> 12:57.600
And the price for pigs is 30 cents each.

12:57.600 --> 13:02.600
You'll have to pay 30 cents each.

13:02.600 --> 13:06.600
That's 60 cents for two.

13:06.600 --> 13:08.600
That's ridiculous.

13:08.600 --> 13:10.600
Replied Mr. Morehouse.

13:10.600 --> 13:14.600
That rule means ordinary pigs, not guinea pigs.

13:14.600 --> 13:20.600
It's obvious the correct rate is 25 cents each.

13:20.600 --> 13:23.600
Mr. Flannery was very stubborn.

13:23.600 --> 13:26.600
Pigs are pigs.

13:26.600 --> 13:30.600
He said the company doesn't care.

13:30.600 --> 13:32.600
They are all pigs.

13:32.600 --> 13:35.600
Pigs are not domestic animals.

13:35.600 --> 13:39.600
And you must pay the rate for pigs.

13:39.600 --> 13:43.600
Mr. Morehouse was silent for a moment.

13:43.600 --> 13:46.600
Very well, he said at last.

13:46.600 --> 13:49.600
I offered you 50 cents and you refused.

13:49.600 --> 13:54.600
I'll write to the president of the company and tell him everything.

13:54.600 --> 13:56.600
Keep the pigs.

13:56.600 --> 13:59.600
But you must look after them very well.

13:59.600 --> 14:02.600
Nothing must happen to them.

14:02.600 --> 14:05.600
Mr. Morehouse left the office.

14:05.600 --> 14:09.600
Mr. Flannery opened the box with the guinea pigs inside.

14:09.600 --> 14:12.600
He looked at them. They were happy.

14:12.600 --> 14:15.600
Mr. Flannery was happy.

14:15.600 --> 14:21.600
He knew the rules about pigs.

14:21.600 --> 14:23.600
Part two.

14:23.600 --> 14:26.600
Letters about pigs.

14:26.600 --> 14:31.600
Mr. Morehouse was very angry when he arrived home.

14:31.600 --> 14:35.600
He wrote a long letter to the president of the company.

14:35.600 --> 14:39.600
He explained the problem about the rate for the guinea pigs.

14:39.600 --> 14:47.600
About a week later, Mr. Morehouse received a letter from the Interurban Express Company.

14:47.600 --> 14:50.600
Interurban Express Company.

14:50.600 --> 14:54.600
Dear sir, please write to the claims department.

14:54.600 --> 14:56.600
Yours faithfully.

14:56.600 --> 15:00.600
Mr. Morehouse now wrote to the claims department of the company.

15:00.600 --> 15:07.600
A few weeks later, he received a reply from the claims department of the Interurban Express Company.

15:07.600 --> 15:10.600
Interurban Express Company.

15:10.600 --> 15:14.600
Dear sir, the pigs are in Mr. Flannery's office.

15:14.600 --> 15:17.600
You did not pay anything to the company.

15:17.600 --> 15:23.600
You must write to the tariff department about the correct rate for the delivery of the pigs.

15:23.600 --> 15:26.600
Yours faithfully.

15:26.600 --> 15:33.600
Mr. Morehouse now wrote to the tariff department of the Interurban Express Company.

15:33.600 --> 15:40.600
The manager of the tariff department, Mr. Morgan, told his secretary to write to Mr. Flannery.

15:40.600 --> 15:43.600
He didn't pay the domestic rate.

15:43.600 --> 15:45.600
Ask him to explain.

15:45.600 --> 15:46.600
He ordered.

15:46.600 --> 15:50.600
And find out the present condition of the animals.

15:50.600 --> 15:54.600
Mr. Flannery received the letter from the tariff department.

15:54.600 --> 15:56.600
Present condition of the animals?

15:56.600 --> 15:57.600
He read.

15:57.600 --> 16:00.600
What does that mean?

16:00.600 --> 16:02.600
I'll look at them.

16:02.600 --> 16:05.600
He walked to the back of the office.

16:05.600 --> 16:07.600
There was a cage there.

16:07.600 --> 16:09.600
Mr. Flannery looked inside.

16:09.600 --> 16:12.600
He began to count carefully.

16:12.600 --> 16:23.600
One, two, three, four, five, six, seven, eight.

16:23.600 --> 16:25.600
He counted.

16:25.600 --> 16:28.600
And all of them very well.

16:28.600 --> 16:35.600
Mr. Flannery went back into his office and wrote to the tariff department of the company.

16:35.600 --> 16:43.600
Dear sir, pigs are pigs.

16:43.600 --> 16:49.600
There are now eight pigs.

16:49.600 --> 16:54.600
They are all well.

16:54.600 --> 16:58.600
They eat a lot.

16:58.600 --> 17:03.600
I paid two dollars for their food.

17:03.600 --> 17:09.600
Will Mr. Morehouse pay for their food?

17:09.600 --> 17:12.600
Yours faithfully.

17:12.600 --> 17:17.600
Mr. Morgan, the head of the tariff department, read Mr. Flannery's letter.

17:17.600 --> 17:19.600
He was very serious.

17:19.600 --> 17:21.600
Flannery is right.

17:21.600 --> 17:23.600
He told his secretary.

17:23.600 --> 17:26.600
Pigs are pigs.

17:26.600 --> 17:30.600
Then he wrote another letter to Mr. Flannery.

17:30.600 --> 17:33.600
Interurban Express Company.

17:33.600 --> 17:38.600
Dear Mr. Flannery, the rules are clear.

17:38.600 --> 17:44.600
When the animals eat food, the customer must pay for it.

17:44.600 --> 17:47.600
Collect the two dollars from Mr. Morehouse.

17:47.600 --> 17:50.600
Yours sincerely, Morgan.

17:50.600 --> 17:52.600
Collect it.

17:52.600 --> 17:56.600
Mr. Flannery thought, I don't know how to do that.

17:56.600 --> 18:03.600
Suddenly he had an idea.

18:03.600 --> 18:04.600
Part three.

18:04.600 --> 18:09.600
Pigs will never be pigs again.

18:09.600 --> 18:13.600
Mr. Flannery drove to Mr. Morehouse's house.

18:13.600 --> 18:17.600
Mr. Morehouse smiled when he came out of the house.

18:17.600 --> 18:20.600
So you've brought the guinea pigs at last?

18:20.600 --> 18:23.600
He said, no sir.

18:23.600 --> 18:25.600
Replied Mr. Flannery.

18:25.600 --> 18:29.600
I've got a bill for two dollars for their food.

18:29.600 --> 18:31.600
Will you pay it?

18:31.600 --> 18:32.600
Two dollars.

18:32.600 --> 18:34.600
Explained Mr. Morehouse.

18:34.600 --> 18:38.600
For food for two guinea pigs, that's ridiculous.

18:38.600 --> 18:40.600
I certainly won't pay it.

18:40.600 --> 18:42.600
There aren't two pigs.

18:42.600 --> 18:47.600
Mr. Flannery told him, there are eight of them now.

18:47.600 --> 18:51.600
Mr. Morehouse closed the door of the house loudly.

18:51.600 --> 18:54.600
Mr. Flannery drove back to his office.

18:54.600 --> 19:00.600
Mr. Flannery wrote again to Mr. Morgan the head of the tariff department.

19:00.600 --> 19:07.600
This time Mr. Morgan spoke to the President of the Interurban Express Company.

19:07.600 --> 19:11.600
Are they domestic pets or are they pigs?

19:11.600 --> 19:14.600
Mr. Morgan wanted to know.

19:14.600 --> 19:18.600
The President thought for a moment, then he said,

19:18.600 --> 19:21.600
I don't know.

19:21.600 --> 19:24.600
I'll write to Professor Gordon.

19:24.600 --> 19:26.600
He's an expert.

19:26.600 --> 19:28.600
He'll know.

19:28.600 --> 19:32.600
Unfortunately, Professor Gordon was in South America.

19:32.600 --> 19:39.600
The letter from the President of the Interurban Express Company arrived after many months.

19:39.600 --> 19:42.600
The President forgot about the problem.

19:42.600 --> 19:45.600
Mr. Morgan forgot about the problem.

19:45.600 --> 19:49.600
Even Mr. Morehouse forgot about the problem.

19:49.600 --> 19:54.600
Mr. Flannery, however, did not forget about the problem.

19:54.600 --> 19:57.600
He wrote again to Mr. Morgan.

19:57.600 --> 20:01.600
Dear Mr. Morgan.

20:01.600 --> 20:05.600
What about these pigs?

20:05.600 --> 20:10.600
There are now 32 of them.

20:10.600 --> 20:14.600
They still eat a lot.

20:14.600 --> 20:19.600
My office is now like a zoo.

20:19.600 --> 20:23.600
Shall I sell the pigs?

20:23.600 --> 20:26.600
You're sincerely Flannery.

20:26.600 --> 20:30.600
Mr. Morgan wrote back immediately.

20:30.600 --> 20:36.600
Dear Mr. Flannery, do not sell the pigs.

20:36.600 --> 20:38.600
They belong to Mr. Morehouse.

20:38.600 --> 20:42.600
The company must continue to look after them.

20:42.600 --> 20:45.600
You're sincerely Morgan.

20:45.600 --> 20:51.600
Mr. Flannery built a special place for the guinea pigs outside the office.

20:51.600 --> 20:55.600
A few months later, he wrote to Mr. Morgan again.

20:55.600 --> 20:58.600
His letter was very short.

20:58.600 --> 21:01.600
Dear Mr. Morgan.

21:01.600 --> 21:04.600
160 pigs.

21:04.600 --> 21:07.600
You're sincerely Flannery.

21:07.600 --> 21:11.600
At last a letter came from Professor Gordon.

21:11.600 --> 21:15.600
He explained everything to the President of the company.

21:15.600 --> 21:17.600
Guinea pigs are not pigs.

21:17.600 --> 21:22.600
They belong to a completely different family and species.

21:22.600 --> 21:25.600
Then the 25 cent rate is the correct one.

21:25.600 --> 21:28.600
The President of the company decided.

21:28.600 --> 21:31.600
Mr. Morgan now wrote to Mr. Flannery.

21:31.600 --> 21:39.600
Dear Mr. Flannery, please deliver the 160 guinea pigs to Mr. Morehouse.

21:39.600 --> 21:44.600
He must pay 25 cents for each guinea pig.

21:44.600 --> 21:47.600
You're sincerely Morgan.

21:47.600 --> 21:51.600
Mr. Flannery wrote back immediately to Mr. Morgan.

21:51.600 --> 21:54.600
Dear Mr. Morgan.

21:54.600 --> 21:58.600
There are not 160 pigs.

21:58.600 --> 22:01.600
There are now 800.

22:01.600 --> 22:06.600
Do I have to charge Mr. Morehouse for 160 or for 800?

22:06.600 --> 22:09.600
You're sincerely Flannery.

22:09.600 --> 22:14.600
The interurban express company considered the problem very carefully.

22:14.600 --> 22:19.600
This took time and the number of guinea pigs increased every day.

22:19.600 --> 22:24.600
Now Mr. Flannery counted 4,064 of them.

22:24.600 --> 22:29.600
At last Mr. Flannery received a letter from the company.

22:29.600 --> 22:31.600
Interurban express company.

22:31.600 --> 22:36.600
Dear Mr. Flannery, collect for two guinea pigs 50 cents.

22:36.600 --> 22:38.600
Deliver them all to Mr. Morehouse.

22:38.600 --> 22:41.600
You're sincerely Morgan.

22:41.600 --> 22:46.600
Once again Mr. Flannery drove to Mr. Morehouse's home.

22:46.600 --> 22:50.600
Mr. Morehouse did not live there anymore.

22:50.600 --> 22:53.600
Mr. Flannery asked the company for orders.

22:53.600 --> 23:00.600
The company told him to send the guinea pigs to the head office of the interurban express company.

23:00.600 --> 23:05.600
Mr. Flannery began to send the cages of guinea pigs to the company.

23:05.600 --> 23:11.600
The company received cages of guinea pigs for days and days.

23:11.600 --> 23:16.600
Mr. Flannery sent 280 cages in one week.

23:16.600 --> 23:20.600
The company now sent him a telegram.

23:20.600 --> 23:23.600
Interurban express company.

23:23.600 --> 23:25.600
Stop sending guinea pigs.

23:25.600 --> 23:28.600
Warehouse full.

23:28.600 --> 23:32.600
And Mr. Flannery sent another telegram back.

23:32.600 --> 23:35.600
Can't stop Flannery.

23:35.600 --> 23:39.600
The company sent an inspector to Mr. Flannery's office.

23:39.600 --> 23:42.600
The company's wagon was full of guinea pigs.

23:42.600 --> 23:45.600
That's the last of them.

23:45.600 --> 23:47.600
Shouted Mr. Flannery angrily.

23:47.600 --> 23:52.600
I'll know what to do with animals next time.

23:52.600 --> 23:55.600
He said, forget the rules.

23:55.600 --> 23:57.600
That's what I'll do.

23:57.600 --> 23:59.600
Pigs are pets.

23:59.600 --> 24:01.600
Cows are pets.

24:01.600 --> 24:03.600
Horses are pets.

24:03.600 --> 24:07.600
And lions and tigers are pets.

24:07.600 --> 24:11.600
Everything goes at 25 cents.

24:11.600 --> 24:15.600
The wagon drove away with the last guinea pigs.

24:15.600 --> 24:19.600
There's one good thing, Mr. Flannery said happily.

24:19.600 --> 24:27.600
At least those pigs weren't elephants.

24:27.600 --> 24:30.600
Listening activity.

24:30.600 --> 24:36.600
You will hear a dialogue between John and his mother.

24:36.600 --> 24:40.600
John, please bring me my glasses.

24:40.600 --> 24:43.600
Here you are, Mum.

24:43.600 --> 24:47.600
John, did you take the dog out this morning?

24:47.600 --> 24:50.600
Yes, I took it out before lunch.

24:50.600 --> 24:53.600
But the rubbish is still here, John.

24:53.600 --> 24:56.600
When are you going to take it away?

24:56.600 --> 24:57.600
Okay, Mum.

24:57.600 --> 25:02.600
I'll bring you a nice cup of tea and then take it out.

25:02.600 --> 25:06.600
Oh, John, would you bring me some biscuits with my tea?

25:06.600 --> 25:08.600
All right, Mum.

25:08.600 --> 25:11.600
And when you go out with the rubbish,

25:11.600 --> 25:14.600
don't forget to take the clothes to the laundry.

25:14.600 --> 25:19.600
And while you're at it, remember to take those films to be developed.

25:19.600 --> 25:22.600
John, are you listening?

25:22.600 --> 25:24.600
John?

25:24.600 --> 25:25.600
John!

25:25.600 --> 25:28.600
Are you listening to me?

25:28.600 --> 25:37.600
Mrs. Packeltide's Tiger by Saki.

25:37.600 --> 25:39.600
Part 1.

25:39.600 --> 25:43.600
Mrs. Packeltide shoots a tiger.

25:43.600 --> 25:47.600
Mrs. Packeltide was in India.

25:47.600 --> 25:50.600
She wanted to kill a tiger.

25:50.600 --> 25:55.600
She wanted to shoot a tiger for a special reason.

25:55.600 --> 26:00.600
A friend, Luna Bimberton, flew in a plane.

26:00.600 --> 26:04.600
Luna talked about the plane all the time.

26:04.600 --> 26:09.600
Mrs. Packeltide was jealous of her friend's adventure.

26:09.600 --> 26:13.600
She wanted an adventure as well.

26:13.600 --> 26:16.600
Mrs. Packeltide had a plan.

26:16.600 --> 26:23.600
She wanted some journalists to take photographs of her with the dead tiger.

26:24.600 --> 26:28.600
Then she wanted to invite Luna Bimberton to lunch

26:28.600 --> 26:32.600
and to give her a tiger claw brooch.

26:32.600 --> 26:36.600
She wanted her friend to be jealous.

26:39.600 --> 26:42.600
Mrs. Packeltide offered the Indians in the village

26:42.600 --> 26:46.600
1,000 rupees for a tiger.

26:47.600 --> 26:52.600
The Indians knew about a very old tiger in the area.

26:53.600 --> 26:56.600
It was not a dangerous animal.

26:56.600 --> 27:01.600
Mrs. Packeltide was very happy.

27:01.600 --> 27:05.600
The Indians prepared a platform high up in a tree

27:05.600 --> 27:10.600
for Mrs. Packeltide and her companion Miss Meben.

27:10.600 --> 27:15.600
The two ladies climbed onto the platform one night.

27:15.600 --> 27:20.600
The Indians put a goat on the ground in front of the tree.

27:20.600 --> 27:24.600
Tigers like to eat goats.

27:24.600 --> 27:31.600
Mrs. Packeltide and Miss Meben waited for the tiger to come.

27:31.600 --> 27:33.600
Is this really dangerous?

27:33.600 --> 27:35.600
Miss Meben asked.

27:35.600 --> 27:36.600
Not at all.

27:36.600 --> 27:38.600
Mrs. Packeltide told her.

27:38.600 --> 27:41.600
The tiger is very old.

27:41.600 --> 27:46.600
He can't jump up into the tree. We're safe here.

27:46.600 --> 27:49.600
Why are you paying 1,000 rupees then?

27:49.600 --> 27:51.600
Miss Meben wanted to know.

27:51.600 --> 27:56.600
The tiger is old. It's not worth 1,000 rupees.

27:56.600 --> 28:00.600
Miss Meben was always interested in money.

28:00.600 --> 28:07.600
She liked to save money. It gave her pleasure to save money.

28:07.600 --> 28:11.600
Suddenly the tiger moved out of the darkness.

28:11.600 --> 28:17.600
It saw the goat on the ground. It came very close.

28:17.600 --> 28:21.600
And then it lay down.

28:21.600 --> 28:23.600
It seemed tired.

28:23.600 --> 28:25.600
It looks ill.

28:25.600 --> 28:28.600
Miss Meben said very loudly.

28:28.600 --> 28:30.600
Be quiet.

28:30.600 --> 28:33.600
Mrs. Packeltide commanded.

28:33.600 --> 28:39.600
The tiger now got up and began to walk towards the goat again.

28:39.600 --> 28:41.600
Shoot now.

28:41.600 --> 28:43.600
Miss Meben suggested.

28:43.600 --> 28:45.600
Don't let it go near the goat.

28:45.600 --> 28:51.600
Then we won't have to pay for the goat. We can save some money.

28:51.600 --> 28:58.600
Mrs. Packeltide picked up her rifle. She fired quickly.

28:58.600 --> 29:02.600
The noise of the rifle was very loud.

29:02.600 --> 29:06.600
The tiger jumped into the air and then fell to the ground.

29:06.600 --> 29:09.600
It did not move.

29:09.600 --> 29:14.600
The Indians were very excited. They immediately ran forward.

29:14.600 --> 29:17.600
They looked at the dead tiger.

29:17.600 --> 29:21.600
They were very pleased.

29:21.600 --> 29:25.600
Mrs. Packeltide was pleased too.

29:25.600 --> 29:29.600
She thought about her friend Luna Bimberton.

29:29.600 --> 29:32.600
Something is wrong.

29:32.600 --> 29:36.600
Louisa Meben said to Mrs. Packeltide.

29:36.600 --> 29:38.600
You shot the goat.

29:38.600 --> 29:42.600
She told Mrs. Packeltide.

29:42.600 --> 29:45.600
She indicated the goat.

29:45.600 --> 29:47.600
It was true.

29:47.600 --> 29:50.600
The goat had a bullet wound.

29:50.600 --> 29:56.600
There was no bullet wound on the tiger, but it too was dead.

29:56.600 --> 30:01.600
The old tiger was dead from a heart attack.

30:01.600 --> 30:05.600
At first Mrs. Packeltide was angry.

30:05.600 --> 30:08.600
Then she thought about it.

30:08.600 --> 30:11.600
She still had a dead tiger.

30:11.600 --> 30:15.600
The Indians had their thousand rupees.

30:15.600 --> 30:20.600
Part two.

30:20.600 --> 30:25.600
Triumph and disaster.

30:25.600 --> 30:28.600
Soon the journalists came.

30:28.600 --> 30:32.600
They took photographs of Mrs. Packeltide and the tiger.

30:32.600 --> 30:35.600
The pictures appeared in many newspapers.

30:35.600 --> 30:39.600
Even the Texas weekly snapshot.

30:39.600 --> 30:42.600
Luna Bimberton saw them.

30:42.600 --> 30:45.600
She was very jealous.

30:45.600 --> 30:49.600
She received the tiger claw brooch.

30:49.600 --> 30:51.600
Then she was angry.

30:51.600 --> 30:57.600
She did not accept Mrs. Packeltide's invitation to lunch.

30:57.600 --> 31:02.600
Mrs. Packeltide and Mrs. Meben returned to London.

31:02.600 --> 31:06.600
They brought the tiger skin with them.

31:06.600 --> 31:09.600
Everyone admired it.

31:09.600 --> 31:15.600
Mrs. Packeltide was very pleased and satisfied with her adventure.

31:15.600 --> 31:18.600
She went to a fancy dress party.

31:18.600 --> 31:21.600
She wore a Diana costume.

31:21.600 --> 31:24.600
No one knows the truth.

31:24.600 --> 31:27.600
Mrs. Meben said a few days later.

31:27.600 --> 31:29.600
What do you mean?

31:29.600 --> 31:32.600
Mrs. Packeltide asked angrily.

31:32.600 --> 31:35.600
You didn't shoot the tiger at all.

31:35.600 --> 31:37.600
Miss Meben explained.

31:37.600 --> 31:39.600
You shot the goat.

31:39.600 --> 31:42.600
The tiger just died because it was afraid.

31:42.600 --> 31:46.600
Miss Meben laughed.

31:46.600 --> 31:50.600
Mrs. Packeltide's face went red.

31:50.600 --> 31:52.600
No one will believe that.

31:52.600 --> 31:54.600
She said quickly.

31:54.600 --> 31:57.600
Luna Bimberton will believe it.

31:57.600 --> 32:00.600
Miss Meben told her quietly.

32:00.600 --> 32:03.600
Mrs. Packeltide went very white.

32:03.600 --> 32:06.600
Don't tell anyone.

32:06.600 --> 32:08.600
She said quietly.

32:08.600 --> 32:11.600
There's a little cottage near Dorking.

32:11.600 --> 32:14.600
Miss Meben replied slowly.

32:14.600 --> 32:17.600
I want to buy it.

32:17.600 --> 32:22.600
It costs 680 pounds.

32:22.600 --> 32:25.600
But I haven't got the money.

32:25.600 --> 32:31.600
Louisa Meben has her little cottage in the country now.

32:31.600 --> 32:34.600
It is a very pretty place.

32:34.600 --> 32:38.600
All her friends like it very much.

32:38.600 --> 32:41.600
How does she pay to keep all this?

32:41.600 --> 32:44.600
They all ask.

32:44.600 --> 32:49.600
Mrs. Packeltide does not hunt tigers anymore.

32:49.600 --> 32:51.600
It's too expensive.

32:51.600 --> 32:56.600
She tells her friends.

32:56.600 --> 32:59.600
Listening activity.

32:59.600 --> 33:02.600
You will hear an interview with Mrs. Packeltide

33:02.600 --> 33:07.600
about how she shot the tiger.

33:07.600 --> 33:08.600
Good evening.

33:08.600 --> 33:14.600
This is Leonard Burner reporting about an extraordinary trophy.

33:14.600 --> 33:20.600
The well-to-do Mrs. Packeltide is very proud about her catch.

33:20.600 --> 33:23.600
A real Indian tiger.

33:23.600 --> 33:28.600
Today she met her friend Luna Bimberton, the well-known pilot,

33:28.600 --> 33:31.600
and gave her a tiger claw brooch.

33:31.600 --> 33:36.600
Mrs. Packeltide, tell us about your adventure.

33:36.600 --> 33:42.600
Yes. Well, good evening to all the lovely listeners out there.

33:42.600 --> 33:44.600
What can I say?

33:44.600 --> 33:48.600
I went to India in the middle of the jungle.

33:48.600 --> 33:52.600
My goodness, with all those beastly animals!

33:52.600 --> 33:56.600
You understand, it's thick jungle,

33:56.600 --> 33:59.600
where you see nothing but wild animals.

33:59.600 --> 34:02.600
Yes, yes. Very dangerous.

34:02.600 --> 34:04.600
Did you go alone?

34:04.600 --> 34:06.600
Well, not exactly.

34:06.600 --> 34:13.600
You see, Miss Louisa Meben, my dear companion, would not let me go alone.

34:13.600 --> 34:19.600
You must understand that I love Miss Meben, but she's not a courageous soul.

34:19.600 --> 34:22.600
I told Miss Meben that it was dangerous.

34:22.600 --> 34:27.600
You mean, Mrs. Packeltide, that Miss Meben did not help you?

34:27.600 --> 34:36.600
Well, I don't want to be rude, but Miss Meben is not the ideal hunting companion.

34:36.600 --> 34:42.600
Well, Mrs. Packeltide, please tell the listeners how you managed to kill the tiger.

34:42.600 --> 34:48.600
You see, I had this rifle, and well, I...

34:48.600 --> 34:52.600
We were walking in the jungle, unprotected.

34:52.600 --> 34:55.600
Yes, do go on.

34:55.600 --> 35:01.600
And, yes, this big Indian tiger appeared suddenly.

35:01.600 --> 35:03.600
How frightening.

35:03.600 --> 35:09.600
Oh, yes, it was awful. It came running out of the thick jungle.

35:09.600 --> 35:10.600
My goodness!

35:10.600 --> 35:13.600
It ran straight towards Miss Meben.

35:13.600 --> 35:15.600
Oh, no!

35:15.600 --> 35:18.600
Exactly! I had to save her life.

35:18.600 --> 35:21.600
So, you shot and saved Miss Meben's life?

35:21.600 --> 35:26.600
Well, you know, she is my companion.

35:26.600 --> 35:28.600
Yes, I understand.

35:28.600 --> 35:33.600
A very brave act, Mrs. Packeltide. A very brave act.

35:33.600 --> 35:37.600
Thank goodness you saved her life.

35:37.600 --> 35:42.600
Yes, thank goodness she's alive.

35:42.600 --> 35:46.600
Well, thank you. Yes, thank you.

35:46.600 --> 35:53.600
No, thank you, Mrs. Packeltide. And this is the end of today's broadcast.

35:56.600 --> 36:06.600
The Stolen White Elephant by Mark Twain. Part 1. A Royal Present.

36:06.600 --> 36:13.600
Once I met a man on a train who told me a story, this is his story.

36:13.600 --> 36:17.600
The White Elephant is a very important animal in Siam.

36:17.600 --> 36:20.600
Only the king can possess one.

36:20.600 --> 36:27.600
Many years ago, Britain and Siam argued about the frontier line of Siam.

36:27.600 --> 36:32.600
Siam was wrong, and the two countries soon became friends again.

36:32.600 --> 36:40.600
The king of Siam decided to send the British Queen a magnificent present, a White Elephant.

36:40.600 --> 36:46.600
It was my job to transport the White Elephant from Siam to England.

36:46.600 --> 36:53.600
We left Siam in a ship with the elephant, and at last we arrived in New York.

36:53.600 --> 36:57.600
We decided to send the elephant to New Jersey for a while.

36:57.600 --> 37:02.600
He needed rest after the first part of the long voyage.

37:02.600 --> 37:08.600
Then a terrible thing suddenly happened. Someone stole the White Elephant.

37:08.600 --> 37:11.600
I went to the New York police.

37:11.600 --> 37:19.600
The chief detective was called Inspector Blunt. He listened to my story in silence.

37:20.600 --> 37:25.600
This is not an ordinary case, he said.

37:25.600 --> 37:31.600
Do not talk to the reporters. I will manage them.

37:31.600 --> 37:36.600
Now, he said, what's the elephant's name?

37:37.600 --> 37:43.600
Hassan Ben, Ali Ben, Selim Abdullah, Mohammed Moise.

37:43.600 --> 37:52.600
Alhamm al-Jamstah jibohoy dulip sultan ebbubudpur. I told him.

37:52.600 --> 37:57.600
Good. First name? Jumbo.

37:57.600 --> 38:00.600
Are his parents living?

38:00.600 --> 38:02.600
No, they're dead.

38:02.600 --> 38:05.600
Was he the only child?

38:05.600 --> 38:07.600
Yes, he was.

38:07.600 --> 38:10.600
Now describe it.

38:10.600 --> 38:16.600
Inspector Blunt commanded me. I began describing the White Elephant.

38:16.600 --> 38:30.600
Height 19 feet, length of trunk 16 feet, length of tail 6 feet, total length including trunk and tail 48 feet.

38:30.600 --> 38:37.600
Color of the elephant, a dull white. He has the habit of spraying people with water.

38:37.600 --> 38:41.600
He has a small scar under his arm.

38:41.600 --> 38:44.600
The detective wrote everything down.

38:44.600 --> 38:47.600
No, I want a photograph.

38:47.600 --> 38:53.600
Inspector Blunt told me. I gave him a photograph of the White Elephant.

38:53.600 --> 38:57.600
Then he rang a bell and a boy came in.

38:57.600 --> 39:05.600
Make 50,000 copies of this description and photograph, Alaric.

39:05.600 --> 39:07.600
He ordered the boy.

39:07.600 --> 39:14.600
Give them to all the detective offices. Alaric left the room.

39:14.600 --> 39:17.600
We will have to offer a reward.

39:17.600 --> 39:19.600
Inspector Blunt told me.

39:19.600 --> 39:22.600
How much? I asked.

39:22.600 --> 39:26.600
To begin with $25,000.

39:26.600 --> 39:28.600
The inspector told me.

39:28.600 --> 39:33.600
These thieves are very clever and they have friends everywhere.

39:33.600 --> 39:39.600
Do you know who they are? I asked in great surprise and astonishment.

39:39.600 --> 39:44.600
We usually have an idea who the criminal is.

39:44.600 --> 39:46.600
He told me.

39:46.600 --> 39:51.600
Inspector Blunt then asked me about the food that the elephant ate.

39:51.600 --> 39:52.600
Men.

39:52.600 --> 39:55.600
Does he eat men?

39:55.600 --> 39:57.600
The inspector asked.

39:57.600 --> 40:00.600
Oh yes, I replied.

40:00.600 --> 40:02.600
But he will eat anything.

40:02.600 --> 40:11.600
He will eat books, bottles, clothes, cats, potatoes, rice, anything at all.

40:11.600 --> 40:14.600
Good, but we need details.

40:14.600 --> 40:18.600
Details are necessary.

40:18.600 --> 40:25.600
During one day, how many men will he eat if they are fresh?

40:25.600 --> 40:29.600
He does not care if they are fresh or not.

40:29.600 --> 40:33.600
At a single meal, he can eat five men.

40:33.600 --> 40:36.600
What nationality does he prefer?

40:36.600 --> 40:41.600
He doesn't care about nationalities, but he prefers people he knows.

40:41.600 --> 40:43.600
What does he drink?

40:43.600 --> 40:46.600
The inspector wanted to know.

40:46.600 --> 40:49.600
He drinks anything as well, I told him.

40:49.600 --> 40:52.600
These are unusual facts.

40:52.600 --> 40:54.600
The inspector commented.

40:54.600 --> 40:59.600
They will help us to find the elephant.

41:02.600 --> 41:05.600
Listening activity.

41:05.600 --> 41:12.600
You will hear a police inspector interviewing someone about a missing person.

41:13.600 --> 41:16.600
This is a strange case.

41:16.600 --> 41:19.600
What is your husband's name?

41:19.600 --> 41:23.600
His name is Arnold Landlow.

41:23.600 --> 41:26.600
Do spell that for me, ma'am.

41:26.600 --> 41:27.600
Yes, of course.

41:27.600 --> 41:39.600
L, A, N, D, L, O, W.

41:39.600 --> 41:43.600
Very good. And where does he live?

41:43.600 --> 41:46.600
Well, he lives with me, of course.

41:46.600 --> 41:48.600
The address, the address.

41:48.600 --> 41:52.600
I need to know his address, please, ma'am.

41:52.600 --> 42:03.600
Yes, we live at 105, 3rd Avenue, New York.

42:03.600 --> 42:06.600
Very good, very good.

42:06.600 --> 42:09.600
And what does he look like?

42:09.600 --> 42:12.600
Oh, inspector.

42:12.600 --> 42:14.600
Dreadful.

42:14.600 --> 42:17.600
He looks just dreadful.

42:17.600 --> 42:23.600
Come on, ma'am. I mean, can you describe him, please?

42:23.600 --> 42:28.600
Well, he's short. Very short.

42:28.600 --> 42:33.600
He's thin. Very thin.

42:33.600 --> 42:38.600
And well, he doesn't have any hair on his head.

42:38.600 --> 42:41.600
He's completely bald.

42:41.600 --> 42:46.600
Oh, but he has hair on the palms of his hands.

42:46.600 --> 42:50.600
Hair on the palms of his hands?

42:50.600 --> 42:52.600
You mean he's a beast?

42:52.600 --> 42:55.600
No, sir. Well, sort of.

42:55.600 --> 43:00.600
No. No, he is a man, you know. He's very clever.

43:00.600 --> 43:08.600
Hmm. You say you lost him after you went shopping with him?

43:08.600 --> 43:12.600
Well, inspector, he lost the keys to the house.

43:12.600 --> 43:16.600
We went to the department store and made a new set of keys.

43:16.600 --> 43:18.600
Then what happened?

43:18.600 --> 43:22.600
Well, he had to go to the barbers for a shave.

43:22.600 --> 43:24.600
Yes, I see.

43:24.600 --> 43:27.600
And well, I went home.

43:27.600 --> 43:31.600
Did you go back to the barbers when he did not come home?

43:31.600 --> 43:37.600
Well, I left the house almost immediately because I had to visit my sick aunt.

43:37.600 --> 43:40.600
Did you return home after that?

43:40.600 --> 43:45.600
Yes, I did. I went home and he wasn't there.

43:45.600 --> 43:47.600
So what did you do then?

43:47.600 --> 43:51.600
I went to the barbers, but he wasn't there.

43:51.600 --> 43:54.600
Can I see the keys to your house?

43:54.600 --> 43:57.600
Of course. Here they are.

43:57.600 --> 44:00.600
Two sets of keys.

44:00.600 --> 44:05.600
Listen here, ma'am. An officer will go to your house with you immediately.

44:05.600 --> 44:09.600
But first, I must examine these sets of keys.

44:09.600 --> 44:15.600
In your statement, you said you only had one set. And well, here we are with two sets.

44:15.600 --> 44:21.600
Part two.

44:21.600 --> 44:25.600
Inspector Blunt gives his orders.

44:25.600 --> 44:30.600
Inspector Blunt now called Captain Burns.

44:30.600 --> 44:35.600
The inspector described the case to him and then he gave his instructions.

44:35.600 --> 44:43.600
Tell Detective Jones, Davis, Bates and Hackett to follow the elephant.

44:43.600 --> 44:52.600
And tell Detective Moses, Dacon, Murphy, Rogers and Bartholomew to follow the thieves.

44:52.600 --> 44:53.600
Yes, sir.

44:53.600 --> 44:55.600
The captain said.

44:55.600 --> 44:58.600
We'll find your elephant.

44:58.600 --> 45:06.600
The inspector told me. I thanked him. I liked that man, and I liked the way he approached the case.

45:06.600 --> 45:11.600
The next morning, the newspapers were full of the story of the stolen elephant.

45:11.600 --> 45:18.600
Some of the newspapers gave the opinions of different detectives about the case.

45:18.600 --> 45:21.600
Each detective had a different opinion.

45:21.600 --> 45:27.600
All the detectives named the criminals, but they all gave different names.

45:27.600 --> 45:33.600
The newspaper articles finished with a mention of Inspector Blunt.

45:33.600 --> 45:39.600
He knows that the criminals are Brick, Duffy and Red McFadden.

45:39.600 --> 45:43.600
He knew that they had plans for the crime.

45:43.600 --> 45:47.600
I was pleased when I read the newspaper article.

45:47.600 --> 45:52.600
It was clear that Inspector Blunt was a very clever detective.

45:52.600 --> 45:56.600
I hurried to his office to talk to him again.

45:56.600 --> 46:00.600
You know who the thieves are, I said.

46:00.600 --> 46:04.600
Why didn't you arrest them before the crime?

46:04.600 --> 46:07.600
We do not prevent crime.

46:07.600 --> 46:12.600
He told me. We punish crime.

46:12.600 --> 46:17.600
We cannot punish it until it is committed.

46:17.600 --> 46:24.600
Then I noticed something strange about the reward for $25,000.

46:24.600 --> 46:27.600
The reward was only for detectives.

46:27.600 --> 46:30.600
What about the public? I asked.

46:30.600 --> 46:34.600
The detectives will find the elephant.

46:34.600 --> 46:36.600
He explained to me.

46:36.600 --> 46:40.600
That is why the reward is for them.

46:40.600 --> 46:48.600
Now the telegraph in the office began to bring in the first messages from the inspector's men.

46:48.600 --> 46:52.600
Flower Station, New York, 7.30 a.m.

46:52.600 --> 46:54.600
Found a clue.

46:54.600 --> 46:58.600
Think the elephant is going west.

46:58.600 --> 47:00.600
I am following.

47:00.600 --> 47:03.600
Darlie, Detective.

47:03.600 --> 47:06.600
Darlie is a good man.

47:06.600 --> 47:08.600
The inspector said.

47:08.600 --> 47:11.600
Another telegram arrived.

47:11.600 --> 47:15.600
Flower Station, New York, 9 a.m.

47:15.600 --> 47:18.600
Followed the tracks for three miles.

47:18.600 --> 47:21.600
A farmer told me they are not elephant tracks.

47:21.600 --> 47:25.600
They are holes he made for planting trees.

47:25.600 --> 47:27.600
Tell me what to do.

47:27.600 --> 47:29.600
Darlie, Detective.

47:29.600 --> 47:33.600
The inspector sent Darlie a telegram.

47:33.600 --> 47:35.600
Arrest the man.

47:35.600 --> 47:39.600
He is one of the thieves.

47:39.600 --> 47:41.600
Follow the tracks.

47:41.600 --> 47:43.600
Inspector Blount.

47:43.600 --> 47:47.600
Next, a telegram arrived from Haws.

47:47.600 --> 47:52.600
Ironville, New York, 9.30 a.m.

47:52.600 --> 47:54.600
The elephant was here this morning.

47:54.600 --> 47:56.600
No one knows where he went.

47:56.600 --> 47:58.600
He killed a horse.

47:58.600 --> 48:01.600
Haws, Detective.

48:01.600 --> 48:04.600
Inspector Blount called Captain Burns.

48:04.600 --> 48:07.600
Send a lot of men to Ironville.

48:07.600 --> 48:09.600
He ordered.

48:09.600 --> 48:14.600
More messages arrived from all over New Jersey and Pennsylvania.

48:14.600 --> 48:17.600
Then a very strange one arrived.

48:17.600 --> 48:20.600
It was from the famous circus Barnum's.

48:20.600 --> 48:27.600
It offered $4,000 a year to use the elephant for advertising the circus.

48:27.600 --> 48:32.600
The idea was to attach advertisements to the elephant's body.

48:32.600 --> 48:35.600
Ridiculous, I cried.

48:35.600 --> 48:37.600
Of course it is.

48:37.600 --> 48:39.600
Inspector Blount agreed.

48:39.600 --> 48:45.600
Mr. Barnum does not know me, but I know him.

48:45.600 --> 48:48.600
The inspector sent a message to Mr. Barnum.

48:48.600 --> 48:52.600
$7,000 or nothing.

48:52.600 --> 48:54.600
Inspector Blount.

48:54.600 --> 48:57.600
Back came an immediate reply.

48:57.600 --> 48:58.600
Agreed.

48:58.600 --> 49:00.600
P.T. Barnum.

49:00.600 --> 49:05.600
A little while later, other telegrams arrived.

49:05.600 --> 49:07.600
Glovers, 11.15 a.m.

49:07.600 --> 49:09.600
Just arrived.

49:09.600 --> 49:12.600
The village is deserted except for the sick and the old.

49:12.600 --> 49:18.600
During a village meeting, the elephant put his trunk in a window and washed the meeting room with water.

49:18.600 --> 49:21.600
Some people drank the water and died.

49:21.600 --> 49:22.600
Others drowned.

49:22.600 --> 49:25.600
The whole region lives in terror.

49:25.600 --> 49:26.600
Brant.

49:26.600 --> 49:27.600
Detective.

49:27.600 --> 49:30.600
Bolivia, New York.

49:30.600 --> 49:32.600
12.50 p.m.

49:32.600 --> 49:36.600
The elephant arrived here and disturbed a funeral procession.

49:36.600 --> 49:38.600
It killed two people.

49:38.600 --> 49:40.600
Several citizens tried to shoot it.

49:40.600 --> 49:42.600
Some of the bullets hit it.

49:42.600 --> 49:46.600
Detective Burke and I followed the animal into the woods.

49:46.600 --> 49:51.600
The elephant stopped to rest and Burke came very close to it.

49:51.600 --> 49:53.600
He shouted out.

49:53.600 --> 49:55.600
The reward is mine.

49:55.600 --> 49:58.600
The elephant turned round and killed him with its trunk.

49:58.600 --> 50:00.600
I ran away.

50:00.600 --> 50:03.600
The elephant chased me back to the funeral procession.

50:03.600 --> 50:06.600
The elephant killed more people.

50:06.600 --> 50:09.600
I do not know where it is now.

50:09.600 --> 50:12.600
Mulroney, Detective.

50:12.600 --> 50:20.600
That was the final telegram that we received.

50:20.600 --> 50:21.600
Part 3.

50:21.600 --> 50:24.600
The End of the Case

50:25.600 --> 50:27.600
I was very unhappy.

50:27.600 --> 50:30.600
The elephant was responsible for many deaths.

50:30.600 --> 50:33.600
And I was responsible for the elephant.

50:33.600 --> 50:39.600
There were more telegrams that day from all over America about the elephant.

50:39.600 --> 50:42.600
But it was clear that no one knew where it was.

50:42.600 --> 50:45.600
It was the same thing the next day.

50:45.600 --> 50:49.600
The newspapers were tired with the story now.

50:49.600 --> 50:52.600
There was nothing exciting to report.

50:52.600 --> 51:00.600
The inspector suggested increasing the reward from $25,000 to $50,000.

51:00.600 --> 51:03.600
Four days passed.

51:03.600 --> 51:06.600
There was still no news of the elephant.

51:06.600 --> 51:16.600
I followed the inspector's advice again and increased the reward from $50,000 to $75,000.

51:16.600 --> 51:20.600
The newspapers now began to attack the detectives.

51:20.600 --> 51:23.600
They made rude comments about them.

51:23.600 --> 51:28.600
Only one man remained calm and that was Inspector Blunt.

51:28.600 --> 51:31.600
I admired him very much.

51:31.600 --> 51:38.600
About three weeks after the elephant disappeared, Inspector Blunt had a brilliant idea.

51:38.600 --> 51:44.600
He decided to contact the thieves and make an agreement with them.

51:44.600 --> 51:48.600
$100,000 will be enough.

51:48.600 --> 51:50.600
He said.

51:50.600 --> 51:53.600
We can't give the thieves $100,000.

51:53.600 --> 51:57.600
I said, the detectives won't get anything.

51:57.600 --> 51:59.600
Yes, they will.

51:59.600 --> 52:01.600
Inspector Blunt told me.

52:01.600 --> 52:07.600
When there is an agreement, the detectives get half of the money.

52:07.600 --> 52:10.600
Inspector Blunt wrote two letters.

52:10.600 --> 52:16.600
One to the wife of Brick Duffy and the other to the wife of Red McFadden.

52:16.600 --> 52:24.600
Dear Madam, your husband can make a lot of money if he comes to see me.

52:24.600 --> 52:30.600
Inspector Blunt, he soon received these replies to the letters.

52:30.600 --> 52:32.600
You old fool.

52:32.600 --> 52:35.600
Brick McDuffie died two years ago.

52:35.600 --> 52:40.600
Chief, they hanged Red McFadden 18 months ago.

52:40.600 --> 52:43.600
Inspector Blunt then had another idea.

52:43.600 --> 52:48.600
He wrote a mysterious advertisement in the morning papers.

52:48.600 --> 52:56.600
He told me this advertisement invited the thief to meet him at midnight the following night.

52:56.600 --> 53:03.600
I arrived at the inspector's office at 11 p.m. the following night with the $100,000.

53:03.600 --> 53:06.600
He took the money and he left the office.

53:06.600 --> 53:08.600
I waited there.

53:08.600 --> 53:10.600
At last he came back.

53:10.600 --> 53:12.600
He looked very happy.

53:12.600 --> 53:15.600
We've made a deal.

53:15.600 --> 53:16.600
Follow me.

53:16.600 --> 53:22.600
I followed the detective down into the basement where the detectives worked.

53:22.600 --> 53:23.600
It was dark there.

53:23.600 --> 53:26.600
The inspector fell over a large object.

53:26.600 --> 53:29.600
Then he cried out excitedly.

53:29.600 --> 53:31.600
The elephant.

53:31.600 --> 53:33.600
I found it.

53:33.600 --> 53:37.600
All the detectives were very happy now.

53:37.600 --> 53:41.600
Everybody congratulated the inspector on his discovery.

53:41.600 --> 53:45.600
Give that man a clue and he'll find anything.

53:45.600 --> 53:47.600
They said happily.

53:47.600 --> 53:53.600
Then they divided the $100,000 and that was a happy occasion too.

53:53.600 --> 53:58.600
The next day the newspapers were full of praise except for one.

53:58.600 --> 54:02.600
It said, what a great detective.

54:02.600 --> 54:07.600
He may be a little slow to find a little thing like a lost elephant.

54:07.600 --> 54:13.600
He hunted him all day and slept with his dead body all night for three weeks.

54:13.600 --> 54:20.600
However he found him at last because the man who lost him showed him the place.

54:20.600 --> 54:22.600
Poor Hassan was dead.

54:22.600 --> 54:25.600
The bullets wounded him fatally.

54:25.600 --> 54:30.600
He reached the detectives' building and there surrounded by his enemies.

54:30.600 --> 54:33.600
He suffered and died of hunger.

54:33.600 --> 54:42.600
This adventure cost me $100,000 plus my detective expenses of $42,000.

54:42.600 --> 54:45.600
I never worked for the government again.

54:45.600 --> 54:49.600
I do not have any money and I am a ruined man.

54:49.600 --> 54:55.600
But I admire Inspector Blunt as the greatest detective in the world.

54:59.600 --> 55:01.600
Listening activity.

55:01.600 --> 55:07.600
Listen to the conversation between a man and a police officer.

55:07.600 --> 55:09.600
Hello.

55:09.600 --> 55:16.600
Is that nine, eight, seven, three, six, five?

55:16.600 --> 55:20.600
Yes it is. How can I help you sir?

55:20.600 --> 55:26.600
I'm calling to claim the $45,000 reward.

55:26.600 --> 55:32.600
The $35,000 reward is for the missing guinea pig.

55:32.600 --> 55:34.600
Where did you find it?

55:34.600 --> 55:44.600
No. I'm claiming the $45,000 reward for the missing needle in the haystack.

55:44.600 --> 55:47.600
Sir, I have good news.

55:47.600 --> 55:54.600
The missing needle in the haystack reward is now worth $100,000.

55:54.600 --> 55:57.600
What do you mean good news?

55:57.600 --> 56:04.600
Do you mean to say it has gone down to $10,000?

56:04.600 --> 56:06.600
No, no sir.

56:06.600 --> 56:10.600
It has gone up to $100,000.

56:10.600 --> 56:16.600
$1,000,000 dollars.

56:16.600 --> 56:18.600
Really?

56:18.600 --> 56:22.600
Tell me what do I have to do?

56:22.600 --> 56:29.600
Well, all you have to do is tell me where you found the needle, sir, and the money is yours.

56:29.600 --> 56:32.600
Why, that's easy.

56:32.600 --> 56:36.600
I've found it in a haystack, of course.

56:36.600 --> 56:38.600
How about that?

56:42.600 --> 56:46.600
The shameful behavior of a fox terrier.

56:46.600 --> 56:52.600
From Three Men and a Boat by Jerome K. Jerome.

56:52.600 --> 56:58.600
Part 1. The Haymarket Stores.

56:58.600 --> 57:04.600
Fox terriers are about four times more mischievous than other dogs.

57:04.600 --> 57:07.600
Their behavior is shameful.

57:07.600 --> 57:13.600
It takes years and years of patience to train them.

57:13.600 --> 57:18.600
I remember what happened in the lobby of the Haymarket stores.

57:18.600 --> 57:23.600
I was in the lobby and there were many dogs all around me.

57:23.600 --> 57:28.600
Their owners were inside the shop, doing their shopping.

57:28.600 --> 57:37.600
There was a bulldog, two collies, a St Bernard, some Yorkshire terriers, a hound, and a French poodle.

57:37.600 --> 57:41.600
There were also a few other smaller dogs.

57:41.600 --> 57:44.600
They were about as big as rats.

57:44.600 --> 57:49.600
They all sat in the lobby patiently and silently.

57:49.600 --> 57:53.600
Then a lovely young lady entered the lobby.

57:53.600 --> 57:57.600
She had a sweet little fox terrier.

57:57.600 --> 58:02.600
She left him there between the bulldog and the poodle.

58:02.600 --> 58:06.600
At first he sat and looked around.

58:06.600 --> 58:13.600
Then he looked up and started looking at the other dogs who were silent and dignified.

58:13.600 --> 58:18.600
First he looked at the bulldog who was asleep on his right.

58:18.600 --> 58:22.600
After he looked at the poodle who was on his left.

58:22.600 --> 58:27.600
Then suddenly the little fox terrier bit the poodle's front leg.

58:27.600 --> 58:31.600
There was a cry of agony in the lobby.

58:31.600 --> 58:36.600
The fox terrier was evidently satisfied with the result of his experiment.

58:36.600 --> 58:41.600
So he decided to continue and create some excitement.

58:41.600 --> 58:45.600
He jumped over the poodle and attacked the collie.

58:45.600 --> 58:49.600
The collie woke up and immediately started fighting with the poodle.

58:49.600 --> 58:53.600
Then the fox terrier returned to his place.

58:53.600 --> 58:58.600
He bit the ear of the bulldog and tried to throw him across the lobby.

58:58.600 --> 59:03.600
The bulldog attacked everything he could find, including the porter.

59:03.600 --> 59:11.600
This gave the dear little fox terrier the opportunity to fight with a brave little Yorkshire terrier.

59:12.600 --> 59:20.600
Anyone who understands dogs will know that by this time there was a great big fight in the lobby with all the dogs.

59:20.600 --> 59:27.600
The big dogs fought the big dogs and the little dogs fought the little dogs.

59:27.600 --> 59:32.600
At times the little dogs bit the legs of the big dogs.

59:32.600 --> 59:36.600
The lobby was in chaos and the noise was terrible.

59:36.600 --> 59:40.600
Soon there was a crowd of people outside the Haymarket stores.

59:40.600 --> 59:44.600
They asked, is there a religious meeting inside?

59:44.600 --> 59:48.600
And is someone killing someone else?

59:48.600 --> 59:50.600
Why?

59:50.600 --> 59:55.600
Some men came with poles and tried to separate the fighting dogs.

59:55.600 --> 59:58.600
Then someone called the police.

59:58.600 --> 01:00:02.600
During the fighting the lovely young lady returned.

01:00:02.600 --> 01:00:09.600
She picked up her sweet little dog who looked at her innocently and she kissed him.

01:00:09.600 --> 01:00:15.600
My poor little dear, what did those big bad dogs do to you?

01:00:15.600 --> 01:00:19.600
The little fox terrier looked at her and seemed to say,

01:00:19.600 --> 01:00:25.600
Oh, thank you for saving me from this horrible fight.

01:00:25.600 --> 01:00:27.600
The young lady said.

01:00:27.600 --> 01:00:34.600
The Haymarket stores must not permit big savage dogs to stay with gentle little dogs.

01:00:34.600 --> 01:00:36.600
This is terrible.

01:00:36.600 --> 01:00:39.600
I must talk to someone about this.

01:00:39.600 --> 01:00:44.600
And this is the nature of fox terriers.

01:00:47.600 --> 01:00:49.600
Part 2.

01:00:49.600 --> 01:00:52.600
Montmorrancy

01:00:52.600 --> 01:00:59.600
Now, the only thing my fox terrier Montmorrancy and I don't agree on is cats.

01:00:59.600 --> 01:01:04.600
I like cats and Montmorrancy doesn't.

01:01:04.600 --> 01:01:08.600
When I meet a cat, I stop and say hello.

01:01:08.600 --> 01:01:10.600
I touch it gently.

01:01:10.600 --> 01:01:14.600
The cat is happy and I am too.

01:01:14.600 --> 01:01:19.600
When Montmorrancy meets a cat, the whole street knows about it.

01:01:19.600 --> 01:01:23.600
A lot of bad words fly through the air.

01:01:23.600 --> 01:01:27.600
Now, I know that my fox terrier is not really bad.

01:01:27.600 --> 01:01:29.600
It is only his nature.

01:01:29.600 --> 01:01:35.600
But something really unforgettable happened when we were in Marlow.

01:01:35.600 --> 01:01:41.600
We went swimming before breakfast and on the way back, Montmorrancy met a cat.

01:01:41.600 --> 01:01:46.600
As soon as he saw the cat, he barked with happiness.

01:01:46.600 --> 01:01:50.600
The cat walked slowly across the street.

01:01:50.600 --> 01:01:53.600
Montmorrancy ran after the cat.

01:01:53.600 --> 01:01:56.600
But the cat didn't run.

01:01:56.600 --> 01:02:00.600
He didn't understand that his life was in danger.

01:02:00.600 --> 01:02:04.600
This cat was big and black.

01:02:04.600 --> 01:02:10.600
It had half a tail, half a nose and only one ear.

01:02:10.600 --> 01:02:14.600
It was a clever street cat.

01:02:14.600 --> 01:02:21.600
Montmorrancy is a courageous dog, but the cold eyes of that cat terrified him.

01:02:22.600 --> 01:02:29.600
The cat stopped in the middle of the road and looked at Montmorrancy with his cold eyes.

01:02:29.600 --> 01:02:35.600
The cat and dog did not speak, but their conversation was probably like this.

01:02:35.600 --> 01:02:39.600
Yes, you want me.

01:02:39.600 --> 01:02:42.600
Can I do anything for you?

01:02:42.600 --> 01:02:44.600
Oh, no thanks.

01:02:44.600 --> 01:02:49.600
If you really want something, please tell me.

01:02:49.600 --> 01:02:50.600
No thanks.

01:02:50.600 --> 01:02:52.600
Nothing at all.

01:02:52.600 --> 01:02:54.600
Very kind of you.

01:02:54.600 --> 01:02:57.600
I am afraid I made a mistake.

01:02:57.600 --> 01:03:00.600
I thought I knew you.

01:03:00.600 --> 01:03:02.600
Sorry I disturbed you.

01:03:02.600 --> 01:03:04.600
Not at all.

01:03:04.600 --> 01:03:06.600
Quite a pleasure.

01:03:06.600 --> 01:03:09.600
Sure you don't want anything now.

01:03:09.600 --> 01:03:11.600
No, nothing at all.

01:03:11.600 --> 01:03:13.600
Very kind of you.

01:03:13.600 --> 01:03:14.600
Good morning.

01:03:14.600 --> 01:03:16.600
Good morning.

01:03:16.600 --> 01:03:19.600
The cat got up and walked away.

01:03:19.600 --> 01:03:24.600
Montmorrancy came back and followed us very quietly.

01:03:24.600 --> 01:03:27.600
He was silent all day long.

01:03:27.600 --> 01:03:35.600
To this day, if you say the word cats to Montmorrancy, he'll stop walking.

01:03:35.600 --> 01:03:45.600
Then he'll look up at you as if to say, oh, please don't.

01:03:45.600 --> 01:03:48.600
Listening activity.

01:03:48.600 --> 01:03:53.600
You will hear only the cats part of the conversation.

01:03:53.600 --> 01:03:59.600
You must pretend to be Montmorrancy and act out his part.

01:03:59.600 --> 01:04:01.600
Yes.

01:04:01.600 --> 01:04:04.600
You want me.

01:04:04.600 --> 01:04:07.600
Can I do anything for you?

01:04:15.600 --> 01:04:29.600
If you really want something, please tell me.

01:04:45.600 --> 01:04:47.600
Not at all.

01:04:47.600 --> 01:04:49.600
Quite a pleasure.

01:04:49.600 --> 01:04:53.600
Sure you don't want anything now.

01:05:09.600 --> 01:05:11.600
Good morning.

01:05:11.600 --> 01:05:20.600
You will hear a recording of parts of the original stories in this book.

01:05:20.600 --> 01:05:26.600
Listen and say which extract is from which story?

01:05:26.600 --> 01:05:28.600
One.

01:05:28.600 --> 01:05:31.600
He took a pen and some paper.

01:05:31.600 --> 01:05:35.600
Now, name of the elephant.

01:05:35.600 --> 01:05:47.600
Hasan ben aliben selim abdala mohamed moist alhamal jam set ji ji boy dulip sultan ebu butpur.

01:05:47.600 --> 01:05:48.600
Very well.

01:05:48.600 --> 01:05:50.600
Given name.

01:05:50.600 --> 01:05:51.600
Jumbo.

01:05:51.600 --> 01:05:52.600
Very well.

01:05:52.600 --> 01:05:54.600
Place of birth.

01:05:54.600 --> 01:05:56.600
The capital city of Siam.

01:05:56.600 --> 01:05:58.600
Parents living?

01:05:58.600 --> 01:05:59.600
No.

01:05:59.600 --> 01:06:00.600
Dead.

01:06:00.600 --> 01:06:03.600
Had they any other issue besides this one?

01:06:03.600 --> 01:06:04.600
None.

01:06:04.600 --> 01:06:07.600
He was an only child.

01:06:10.600 --> 01:06:11.600
Two.

01:06:11.600 --> 01:06:13.600
Do as you like, then.

01:06:13.600 --> 01:06:14.600
Shouted Flannery.

01:06:14.600 --> 01:06:19.600
Pay for him and take him or don't pay for him and leave him be.

01:06:19.600 --> 01:06:22.600
Rules is rules, Mr. Morehouse.

01:06:22.600 --> 01:06:27.600
And Mike Flannery's not going to be called down for breaking of them.

01:06:28.600 --> 01:06:38.600
But you everlastingly stupid idiot shouted Mr. Morehouse, madly shaking a flimsy printed book beneath the agent's nose.

01:06:38.600 --> 01:06:44.600
Can't you read it here in your own plain printed rates?

01:06:44.600 --> 01:06:45.600
Pets.

01:06:45.600 --> 01:06:46.600
Domestic.

01:06:46.600 --> 01:06:50.600
Franklin to West Coast is properly boxed.

01:06:50.600 --> 01:06:53.600
25 cents each.

01:06:53.600 --> 01:06:57.600
He threw the book on the counter in disgust.

01:06:57.600 --> 01:07:00.600
What more do you want?

01:07:00.600 --> 01:07:02.600
Aren't they pets?

01:07:02.600 --> 01:07:04.600
Aren't they domestic?

01:07:04.600 --> 01:07:06.600
Aren't they properly boxed?

01:07:06.600 --> 01:07:07.600
What?

01:07:11.600 --> 01:07:19.600
In the high and far off times, the elephant, O best beloved, had no trunk.

01:07:19.600 --> 01:07:30.600
He had only a blackish, bulgy nose, as big as a boot, that he could wriggle about from side to side.

01:07:30.600 --> 01:07:34.600
But he couldn't pick up things with it.

01:07:34.600 --> 01:07:46.600
But there was one elephant, a new elephant, an elephant's child, who was full of insatiable curiosity.

01:07:46.600 --> 01:07:52.600
And that means he asked ever so many questions.

01:07:55.600 --> 01:08:10.600
I remember being in the lobby of the Haymarket stores one day, and all round about me were dogs, waiting for the return of their owners, who were shopping inside.

01:08:10.600 --> 01:08:21.600
There were a mastiff, and one or two collies, and a St. Bernard, a few retrievers and new fountains,

01:08:21.600 --> 01:08:31.600
a boarhound, a fringe poodle, with plenty of hair around its head, but mangy about the middle,

01:08:31.600 --> 01:08:42.600
a bulldog, a few lather arcade sort of animals, about the size of rats, and a couple of Yorkshire tikes.

01:08:42.600 --> 01:08:52.600
There they sat, patient, good and thoughtful, a solemn peacefulness.

01:08:53.600 --> 01:09:01.600
It was Mrs. Packeltide's pleasure and intention that she should shoot a tiger,

01:09:01.600 --> 01:09:06.600
not that the lust to kill had suddenly descended on her,

01:09:06.600 --> 01:09:13.600
or that she felt that she would leave India safer and more wholesome than she had found it,

01:09:13.600 --> 01:09:20.600
with one fraction less of wild beast per million of inhabitants.

